The paper deals with algorithms for estimating random walk probabilities on graphs, which is a problem in graph algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The focus on small space complexity suggests that it may also be relevant to the subfield of space-efficient algorithms (cs.CC). The use of spectral methods and approximation techniques suggests that it may be relevant to machine learning and data analysis (cs.LG, cs.SI). Finally, the use of matrix inversion algorithms suggests that it may be relevant to information theory and coding theory (cs.IT).
